presented the document to President Zardari at a meeting in Islamabad.
It said the report "concluded that the blasphemy case against Asia Bibi has been
registered on grounds of personal enmity".
The document recommended providing security both to Bibi in prison and to her
family, who say they have gone into hiding because of death threats.
In the meeting Bhatti, who himself is a Christian and was commissioned by
Zardari to investigate the case, said the minority community "has great respect
for all the Holy Prophets and the Holy Books," the statement said.
"The people belonging to minorities as a marginalised community know fully well
the consequences of blasphemy and could never think of committing the offence,"
it quoted him as saying.
The president asked Bhatti to draw up a committee to propose reforms to the
blasphemy law to "effectively prevent the misuse of (it) for personal and
political reasons," the statement added.
Pope Benedict XVI last week called for Bibi's release and said Christians in
Pakistan were "often victims of violence and discrimination."
Punjab governor Salman Taseer on Sunday was the first senior government official
to appeal to Zardari for clemency after visiting Bibi in prison.
The case began in June 2009 when Bibi was asked to fetch water while out working
in the fields. Muslim women labourers objected, saying that as a non-Muslim, she
should not touch the water bowl.
Bibi was later arrested by police and prosecuted after Muslim women complained
that she made derogatory remarks about the Prophet Mohammed.
Rights activists and pressure groups say it is the first time that a woman had
been sentenced to hang in Pakistan for blasphemy.
Only around three percent of Pakistan's population of 167 million are estimated
to be non-Muslim.
